{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015bTqSfoCLkwRM36axKrJVJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the STT API output contains speaker labels. The failure mode is: STT API doesn't return speaker labels (or returns them in unexpected format), breaking downstream attribution. This requires calling the real STT API or a realistic fake of it. If we're testing the pipeline's handling of speaker labels, we need at least Integration (STT module + transcript parser). But the question is whether this is about the STT API quality (Agentic/System) or about the code that processes speaker labels (could be Unit/Integration).\n\n\n- REAL-INFRA: The actual behavior depends on two things—whether the code requests speaker diarization from the STT service with the right parameters, and whether the real STT API reliably returns those labels. This is a System-level concern since it involves the actual HTTP call to the STT service and its response format.\n\n- LLM-DEP: STT isn't an LLM and is deterministic for the same audio input, so the question becomes whether the real STT API actually preserves speaker labels in its response. An in-process mock would only test our mock implementation, not whether the real service actually supports this feature.\n\nThe core issue is whether our code correctly requests and handles speaker diarization from the real STT API—this requires testing against actual infrastructure to verify the behavior works end-to-end.\n\n**Behavior 2: Structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.**\n\nThis is about LLM output quality—whether the model correctly identifies and attributes action items to the right attendees.\n\nThis is Agentic. The LLM's ability to catch all action items and assign them accurately is non-deterministic and varies across runs, so testing against real LLM output is necessary.\n\n**Behavior 3: Key decisions mentioned in the transcript appear in the \"decisions\" section, not buried in the narrative.**\n\nAgain, this depends on the LLM's classification ability—whether it properly separates decisions from narrative content.\n\nThis is Agentic. The correctness hinges on what the actual LLM produces.\n\n**Behavior 4: When audio file > 60 minutes, service splits into segments, processes sequentially, merges results into single coherent summary.**\n\nThe splitting logic itself could be unit-tested with fake audio data, and the sequential processing of STT and LLM modules is integration-level. But the merging step introduces LLM dependency—if we're validating that the final summary is coherent, that's LLM-dependent, though testing the structural correctness of how results are merged could be done at integration level without relying on coherence.\n\nThis is really a workflow-level test because it involves multiple agentic steps in sequence: splitting audio, running STT on each segment, summarizing each with an LLM, then merging those summaries into a final coherent output. The real failure modes are splitting errors, missing segments, merge logic failures, and coherent merging across segments—the last one being LLM-dependent. Since the behavior explicitly requires \"merging into a single coherent summary,\" that coherence quality is what makes this workflow-level rather than just integration.\n\nFor the full pipeline behavior, this is clearly end-to-end with real infrastructure: uploading actual audio, calling real STT APIs, running real LLM summarization, and delivering structured output without manual intervention. That's multiple sequential agentic steps across the entire system.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 needs a real STT API call to verify speaker labels are preserved correctly, so System testing dominates. Behavior 2 is primarily about LLM output quality for extracting action items, making it Agentic-heavy. Behavior 3 involves LLM classification of decisions...\n\nBehavior 4 spans multiple sequential LLM steps, so Workflow testing becomes more significant. Behavior 5 is the full end-to-end pipeline, which is almost entirely Workflow-level testing.\n\nNow I'm finalizing the test descriptions and justifications, starting with Behavior 1 where the critical failure mode is whether the STT API actually supports speaker diarization or returns meaningful labels.\n\nFor Behavior 1, I need a real HTTP call to the STT API with actual audio containing multiple speakers to verify the transcript includes speaker labels for each utterance. The minimum level is System because a mock would hide whether diarization truly works.\n\nBehavior 2 depends on what the LLM actually extracts and attributes—a mock LLM would mask real failures in action item extraction or misattribution. Running it 100 times would reveal whether the LLM's output is consistent enough for reliable action item detection, which pushes this to Agentic level.\n\nFor Behavior 3, I'm checking whether the LLM correctly categorizes decisions into the decisions field rather than burying them in narrative. This requires a real LLM call with a transcript containing explicit decisions to verify the categorization logic works as intended.\n\nFor Behavior 4, the multi-step workflow involves splitting audio into segments, summarizing each one separately, then merging them into a coherent whole—something that can't be validated without real LLM calls across the full pipeline to ensure the merged output maintains consistency and clarity.\n\nFor Behavior 5, this is the complete end-to-end test with all real dependencies: actual audio upload, real speech-to-text conversion, real LLM processing, and structured output delivery. The test verifies that the entire pipeline runs autonomously and produces populated action items, decisions, and attendee attribution fields without any manual intervention.\n\nNow I'm checking whether each behavior's test plan aligns with its minimum level requirement.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9724,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9724},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95522b46-facd-4a78-a6cb-67ad7c9d8781","uuid":"71bdb004-af0b-415e-863b-ddee2d7e90e6"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015bTqSfoCLkwRM36axKrJVJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VXCCqwqUYzt6uAgQPDNVys","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels for attendee attribution.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The real failure mode is that the STT API either does not support speaker diarization, requires a specific request parameter to enable it, or returns labels in an unexpected schema. An in-process fake always returns whatever speaker labels we hardcode, so it cannot catch these failures. A real HTTP call to the STT API is required. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: STT diarization is deterministic for the same audio input — repeated calls produce consistent speaker IDs — so LLM-style non-determinism does not apply.","test_description":"Submit a pre-recorded audio clip containing two or more distinct speakers to the real speech-to-text API and assert the returned transcript object contains a non-null speaker_label (or equivalent diarization field) on every utterance, covering all expected speaker IDs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.52,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure is the LLM omitting or misattributing action items from the transcript. A mocked LLM returns pre-programmed output, so it can never expose this failure — the test would pass regardless of LLM quality. Correctness here is inherently non-deterministic across LLM runs. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: this behavior exercises a single summarization call; no multi-step agentic chain is required to catch the failure.","test_description":"Feed a curated transcript containing explicit, named task assignments (e.g., 'Alice, please send the report by Friday; Bob, schedule the vendor call') to the live LLM summarizer and assert that action_items in the returned structured output contains at least one item attributed to each named assignee.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.13}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Key decisions appear in the 'decisions' section, not buried in the narrative.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure is the LLM categorizing decision content into the narrative field rather than the decisions field. A mocked LLM would produce whatever structure we hardcode, making the test trivially pass regardless of LLM behavior. The categorization judgment is inherently LLM-dependent and can vary across runs. REJECTION-GATE for Workflow: only a single LLM summarization call is exercised; no sequential multi-step chain is needed to observe the failure.","test_description":"Provide a transcript containing several clearly-worded decisions (e.g., 'We decided to launch in Q3', 'The team agreed to switch vendors') to the real LLM summarizer and assert that those decision statements appear in the decisions field of the structured output, while the narrative field does not contain equivalent text.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.13}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Audio longer than 60 minutes is split into segments, processed sequentially, and merged into a single coherent summary.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This behavior requires: (a) the segmentation boundary to trigger, (b) each segment to be independently transcribed and summarized via real LLM calls, and (c) the merge step to produce a coherent unified summary. The coherence claim across segments can only be verified with real LLM calls, and the full sequence constitutes multiple agentic steps in sequence. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic (single step): a single Agentic test covers one LLM call; it cannot verify cross-segment coherence or that the sequential-merge pipeline produces consistent output end-to-end. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: structural merging (field concatenation) can be tested at Integration, but the 'single coherent summary' quality claim cannot.","test_description":"Submit a >60-minute audio recording (or a synthetic fixture that triggers the segment threshold) through the full pipeline with real LLM calls enabled. Assert that: (a) the service emits log/event evidence of multiple segment calls, (b) each segment produces a partial structured summary, and (c) the final merged output is a single structured document containing action items and decisions drawn from content present in all segments, with no duplicate or contradictory entries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.23,"Workflow":0.5}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is an explicit end-to-end pipeline test. Every stage requires real infrastructure: real audio upload (OS/network I/O), real STT HTTP API call, real LLM summarization call, and real structured output delivery. The behavior specifically requires a real meeting recording and autonomous completion. No single lower level can expose failures at the handoff boundaries between pipeline stages. MULTI-STEP: upload → transcribe (STT) → summarize (LLM) → deliver is a multi-step agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Upload a real meeting audio recording to the service endpoint, poll or subscribe for completion without any manual step, and assert the delivered structured output: (a) has non-empty action_items list, (b) has non-empty decisions list, (c) has attendee attributions linking statements to real speaker names from the recording, and (d) the entire run completes within a defined SLA timeout with no human-in-the-loop prompts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.81}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9724,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9724},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95522b46-facd-4a78-a6cb-67ad7c9d8781","uuid":"4899c266-f636-400d-ac48-8d1c3ec8f3ca"}
